snippet.textDisplay:
She does not hide her age in her voice, instead she wraps it in paisleys, and for a moment holds it in both of her hands, before she drowns it in our sky. When she sings now, she knows that at the end of that note when her voice breaks like a wishbone, he will stay.

Waqt ki qaid mei zindagi hai magar..

snippet.textDisplay: Aaj Jaane Ki Zid Na Karo [Please don't insist on leaving today] is a Ghazal written by Fayyaz Hashmi. (Wikipedia)

snippet.textDisplay: What a beautiful song. I fall in love with Farida Ji again and again whenever I hear her. And this song is amazing. Beautiful lyrics, beautiful music and a beautiful voice. She is the living legend. Would like to visit Pakistan someday. My grandparents both maternal and paternal before the partition were in Sialkot and Multan respectively.  They tell me the stories about the painful partition, how they lost everything. They came here got married in 1950. Why can't we forget hatred and love each other. We all have rich culture. We were one before partition then y so much of hatred. Our culture is similar, our food habits, music, pehnawa, even humans are same with 2 eyes, 2 ears, one nose, 2 hands and legs then y do we keep fighting. U people have amazing musicians. Love and respect from India.
